Task: How would I create a shared memory buffer to display animations using the Kitty Graphics Protocol in Rust?

 <p>I'm using Arch Linux with Wayland. My terminal is Kitty.
I'm trying to create an animation using the Kitty Graphics Protocol. However, I want this animation to cover the whole screen and run at 60 fps.</p>
<p>I'm trying to use base64 for this, but it's just way too slow. I also have to break up the data into chunks to get it all to fit, which isn't really ideal.
Based on <a href="https://sw.kovidgoyal.net/kitty/graphics-protocol/#the-transmission-medium" rel="nofollow noreferrer">this</a>, I think a solution to this would be using shared memory buffers instead, but I don't really know how to implement them. I've seen them used <a href="https://github.com/chase/awrit/" rel="nofollow noreferrer">here</a>, but haven't really been able to reproduce what's on there.</p>
<p>This is my current base64 code:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>use std::io::{self, Write};
use base64::{engine::general_purpose::STANDARD, Engine};
use termion::terminal_size_pixels;

const CHUNK_SIZE: usize = 4096;

fn main() {
    let stdout = io::stdout();
    let mut handle = stdout.lock();

    let mut time: f32 = 0.0;

    let (width, height) = terminal_size_pixels().unwrap_or((640, 480));
    let (width, height) = (width as usize, height as usize);

    loop {
        // Generate animated RGB gradient pixel data
        let pixels: Vec&lt;u8&gt; = (0..height)
            .flat_map(|y| {
                (0..width).flat_map(move |x| {
                    let fx = x as f32 / width as f32;
                    let fy = y as f32 / height as f32;

                    let r = ((fx * std::f32::consts:: PI + time).sin() * 0.5 + 0.5) * 255.0;
                    let g = ((fy * std::f32::consts::PI + time * 1.3).sin() * 0.5 + 0.5) * 255.0;
                    let b = (((fx + fy) * std::f32:: consts::PI + time * 0.7).sin() * 0.5 + 0.5) * 255.0;

                    [r as u8, g as u8, b as u8]
                })
            })
            .collect();

        write!(handle, &quot;\x1b[H&quot;).unwrap();

        let encoded = STANDARD.encode(&amp;pixels);
        let chunks: Vec&lt;&amp;str&gt; = encoded
            .as_bytes()
            .chunks(CHUNK_SIZE)
            .map(|c| std::str::from_utf8(c).unwrap())
            .collect();

        for (i, chunk) in chunks.iter().enumerate() {
            let is_first = i == 0;
            let is_last = i == chunks.len() - 1;
            let m = if is_last { 0 } else { 1 };

            if is_first {
                write!(
                    handle,
                    &quot;\x1b_Ga=T,f=24,s={},v={},m={};{}\x1b\\&quot;,
                    width, height, m, chunk
                ).unwrap();
            } else {
                write!(
                    handle,
                    &quot;\x1b_Gm={};{}\x1b\\&quot;,
                    m, chunk
                ).unwrap();
            }
        }

        handle.flush().unwrap();

        time += 0.1;
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>If there's a faster/better way to do this, I would really like to hear it.</p>


